hook.real_world_problem:
Razorpay calls Visa's payment network. Visa occasionally drops connections under load — 30% of failed calls succeed on immediate retry:

```
Without retry:
  Call 1: IOException (network blip) → payment FAILED
  User: 'My payment failed' → support ticket → refund request
  Reality: Visa was ready 50ms later

With @Retry:
  Call 1: IOException → wait 100ms → retry
  Call 2: SUCCESS → payment APPROVED
  User: sees 100ms extra latency (imperceptible)
  Support tickets: zero for this failure type
```

```java
@Retry(name = "visa-gateway", fallbackMethod = "paymentFailed")
@CircuitBreaker(name = "visa-gateway")
public PaymentResult chargeVisa(ChargeRequest req) {
    return visaClient.charge(req);
}
// @Retry retries on transient failures
// @CircuitBreaker opens if retry-exhausted failures pile up
```

Separate concern: your service calls a rate-limited analytics API (1,000 calls/hour):
```java
@RateLimiter(name = "analytics-api")
public void logEvent(TradeEvent event) {
    analyticsClient.record(event);
}
// If you exceed 1,000/hour: RequestNotPermittedException
// Rate limiter enforces the quota YOUR service respects toward the downstream API
```

concept_explanation.retry:
**@Retry — transparent transient failure recovery:**

```yaml
# application.yml:
resilience4j:
  retry:
    instances:
      visa-gateway:
        maxAttempts: 3           # total attempts (1 original + 2 retries)
        waitDuration: 100ms      # wait between attempts
        enableExponentialBackoff: true
        exponentialBackoffMultiplier: 2.0
        # Attempt 1: immediate
        # Attempt 2: +100ms
        # Attempt 3: +200ms (100 × 2.0)
        # Total max wait: 300ms
        retryExceptions:         # ONLY retry these exception types
          - java.io.IOException
          - java.net.ConnectException
        ignoreExceptions:        # NEVER retry these (permanent errors)
          - com.razorpay.InvalidCardException
          - com.razorpay.InsufficientFundsException
```

```java
import io.github.resilience4j.retry.annotation.Retry;

@Service
public class VisaGatewayService {

    @Retry(name = "visa-gateway", fallbackMethod = "visaFallback")
    public PaymentResult charge(ChargeRequest req) {
        // If IOException: retried up to 3 times
        // If InvalidCardException: NOT retried (in ignoreExceptions)
        return visaClient.charge(req);
    }

    private PaymentResult visaFallback(ChargeRequest req, Exception e) {
        // Called after ALL retries exhausted:
        log.error("Visa charge failed after {} retries: {}", 3, e.getMessage());
        return PaymentResult.failed("GATEWAY_ERROR");
    }
}
```

concept_explanation.rate_limiter:
**@RateLimiter — respect downstream API quotas:**

```yaml
resilience4j:
  ratelimiter:
    instances:
      analytics-api:
        limitForPeriod: 100      # max 100 calls per refresh period
        limitRefreshPeriod: 1s   # reset every 1 second
        timeoutDuration: 500ms   # wait up to 500ms for a permit
```

```java
import io.github.resilience4j.ratelimiter.annotation.RateLimiter;
import io.github.resilience4j.ratelimiter.RequestNotPermittedException;

@Service
public class AnalyticsService {

    @RateLimiter(name = "analytics-api", fallbackMethod = "dropEvent")
    public void recordTradeEvent(TradeEvent event) {
        analyticsClient.record(event);  // external API with rate limit
    }

    private void dropEvent(TradeEvent event, RequestNotPermittedException e) {
        // Rate limit exceeded — drop or queue the event:
        log.warn("Analytics rate limit hit — dropping event {}", event.getId());
        // Or: queue.offer(event) for retry
    }

    // Rate limiter vs our rate limiter (Topic 18.3):
    // Topic 18.3 (Redis INCR): protects OUR service from INCOMING abuse
    // @RateLimiter:            protects THEIR service from OUR outgoing calls
}
```

concept_explanation.combining:
**Combining @Retry + @CircuitBreaker:**

```java
// Order matters: outer annotation wraps inner
// Best practice: @CircuitBreaker OUTSIDE @Retry
@CircuitBreaker(name = "notification", fallbackMethod = "notifCBFallback")
@Retry(name = "notification")  // @Retry is INSIDE the circuit breaker
public void sendNotification(String userId, String message) {
    notifClient.send(userId, message);
}
// Execution order:
// CB checks state → if CLOSED: Retry wraps the actual call
// If all retries fail: CB records ONE failure (not 3)
// If CB opens: all calls fast-fail without even attempting retry

// The number each circuit breaker counts:
// @Retry(maxAttempts=3) fails → CB records 1 failure
// After N CB-failures at threshold → circuit OPENS
// Future calls: CB fast-fails before even trying the first retry

// WRONG order (retry outside CB): CB records each retry attempt as a separate failure
// → Circuit opens much faster than intended
```

